Most V/LLM models can be found in various quantizations
→ **model_name_Q#**
Lower quantizations are smaller in file size, run faster and work with lower hardware specs, but are less accurate in return.
→ **Q4_K_M** quants are usually a solid and efficient pick
> The ComfyUI_VLM_nodes pack requires the V/LLMs in **.gguf** format.

# ControlNet --- ## Image Input - **Load CNet Image + Crop + Image Resize**
→ loads image and allows adjusting crop and size
→ Important : Flux Tools takes the image size as the input latent size → right-click on **Preview Image** to queue and check the cropped/resized image

--- ## Flux Tools > LoRA-based ControlNet - **Flux Tools LoRA**
– select your LoRA of FluxTools LoRA here
→ LoRA strength reflects the intensity
→ recommended range: 0.3 - 0.8
> **SVDQ issue**: Does not work with **TiledDiffusion** in the **2nd Pass** → error
→ A signal is in place to safeguard against that issue automatically.
Regular Sampling as well as **USDU** work without issue.
--- ## Image Padding > automatically pads the image to fit the chosen latent size by stretching the edges to the needed dimension
→ helps prevent frame-effect around the image

## Flux Redux > compatible with **SVDQ** and **TiledDiffusion** without issue ### Load Style Model > select ***fluxToolsRedux_reduxDev.safetensors*** here ### Load CLIP Vision > select ***sigclip_vision_patch14_384.safetensors*** here ### image_X_strength >*(has a 0.5 multiplier to make it easier to control)* - usual values ~ 0.5 - 0.9 ### image_X_start | image_X_end > the timing allows targetting ranges : - ~ 0.0 - 0.3 → for more composition - ~ 0.3 - 1.0 → for more style control ### Use Both Images ? > allows mixing both image inputs ### Redux for 1st / 2nd Pass ? > to target individual passes   --- ## Redux / PuLID Input images are center cropped in the process, so using square formats is recommended ### Default Image Loader - Load Image 1 | Load Image 2 > loads images directly from the `ComfyUI\input` folder ### Random Image Loader - Random Image from Folder > loads images found at the entered path
→ uses a seed which allows randomization

## PuLID ### Load PuLID Flux Model > select ***pulid_flux_v0.9.x.safetensors*** here ### Resolution > size the input images are scaled to ### Apply PuLID Flux - **weight**
– strength of the effect → solid values: 0.6 - 0.9
- **fusion**
→ *mean* : averages the image embeds
→ *train_weight* : a method aiming to improve the default mean   --- ## Redux / PuLID Input images are center cropped in the process, so using square formats is recommended ### Default Image Loader - Load Image 1 | Load Image 2 > loads images directly from the `ComfyUI\input` folder ### Random Image Loader - Random Image from Folder > loads images found at the entered path
→ uses a seed which allows randomization

## LLM Prompt Assitance ### LLava Loader Simple - **ckpt** – loads the LLM **model.gguf**
- **max_ctx** – amount of tokens used for the LLM's context ("memory")
### Llava Clip Loader - **clip** – loads the **mmproj.gguf** from the LLM model
### Instruction - prompt for the LLM to get the output-prompt you want
### Structured Output - **temperature** – setting to control the amount of "creativity"
→ since there is no seed unfortunately changing the temperature or parts of the prompt are the only way to get different outputs
- **attribute_description | categories** → works in mysterious ways, but can help randomize a little
→ can both be left empty or used with keywords to focus on fitting your prompt, e.g. "character", "person", "protagonist", will change the outcome. - **Preview Output** > Will show the generated output and is only minimized to save space.

# LoRA Settings
### Accelerator + LoRA 1-6 - LoRAs are automatically appended to the positive prompt metadata
→ the **Accelerator** position at the top is not different in any way and only labeled out of personal preference
### Strength Sliders >Preset to the most common range of **0-1.0** - to enter specific values, double-click the number

→ *(right-click context menu)*
- holding the **ctrl** key while pulling the slider against one of the edges allows exceeding the preset range

# Core Settings
### Patch Sage Attention KJ - Enables/Disables SageAttention
→ requires [**Triton**](https://github.com/woct0rdho/triton-windows) and [**SageAttention**](https://github.com/thu-ml/SageAttention) to be installed
### DeDistilled Model - Enables use of regular CFG for DeDistilled models
### Model Sampling Flux - **base_shift | max_shift**
higher values increase creative freedom during generation, but also the likelihood of deviations from the prompt
→ similar to "temperature" variable with LLMs
→ Flux Schnell models are only affected by **base_shift**
### TeaCache > Speeds up generation significantly, while retaining a good level of quality
→ lowering **rel_l1_thresh** reduces the speed increase, but preserves more of the original quality   ### Compile Model - Processes the model to further speed up generation
→ might take a bit to go through the compiling process *(few seconds in my experience)*, but the speed increase is noticeable
→ the compiling process is repeated when the latent size changes, i.e. the outpainting parameters are tweaked
### Image Dimensions > Quick and dynamic resolution selection for the empty latent - to enter specific values, double-click the numbers
- value ranges and steps can be tweaked within the **Properties Panel**
→ *(right-click context menu)* --- ## SVDQuant Info - **SageAttention** → works fine
- **TeaCache** → Error
- **Compile Model** → Error > FYI: The error cases are circumvented automatically when using SVDQ models regardless of setting

## Complete Overhaul Since ComfyUI began deprecation of group nodes **before** implementing the SubGraph feature which is supposed to replace it **soon**™, I had to disassemble all group nodes in all my workflows.
## New Version The result is inevitably taking up more space and includes a "little" more wiring chaos than you might be used to from my workflows.

However, this workflow is still nonetheless an **upgrade** to the previous versions in all areas except the *area* it takes up.
## Group Nodes An advantage of group nodes was the ability to handle value ranges, calculations, metadata etc. without cluttering the view.
I also renamed various settings to better describe their function, while trying to shorten the labels in general.
On top of that many settings which served barely any purpose, could be handled automatically or were irrelevant within the context they were in, could simply be hidden.
## Changes Going forward I try to get all nodes that require no tweaking out of view, turn them nameless and stack them away.
This means you can ignore all collapsed nodes as they won't need configuring. In case of unimportant but nice-to-have/personal preference type settings I will point them out and highlight the nodes subtly to make you aware of them; e.g. when fonts or colors can be tweaked as preferred. --- ## TLDR - Collapsed, nameless, black nodes can and should be ignored
- Optional, functionally unimportant settings will be mentioned and the nodes highlighted as ♦️red node♦️
- All ksamplers that are expanded only serve as a live-preview.
→ potentially exposed settings on them should be left alone

# 2nd Pass ### Upscaling - **scale_by** – defines upscale factor (1.0 = **no upscale**)
- **Use Upscale Model ?** *(Ultimate Upscale always runs the selected model regardless)* **true** → uses selected upscale model **false** → regular upscale ### Sampling - **Flux Guidance** → Flux Guidance with built in OFF-switch when set to **-0.1**
—*(usually best for SVDQ models)*
- **daemon_detail_amount** → positive values leave some noise to turn into detail
→ negative values denoise more, creating cleaner results

→ ***Detail Daemon Sampler** contains further settings for timing etc. to experiment with, but can generally be left alone.
Highlighted as a ♦️red node♦️ above the **SamplerCustomAdvanced***
### Tiled Sampling - **tile_size + tile_overlap** → only applies when Tiled Diffusion or Ultimate Upscale is used
- **tile_batch_size** – amount of tiles processed at once → reduce if low on VRAM
- **Use Tiled Diffusion ? + Use Ultimate Upscale ?** → regular sampling if both are set to **false**

**Tiled Diffusion**
→ faster
→ recommended denoise < 0.4

**Ultimate SD Upscale**
→ slower
→ recommended denoise < 0.3

### Color Correction > matches colors from previous pass - **strength**
→ 1.0 is usually good (0.0 = **off**)

# ADetailer ### Detection - **bbox_detector** *(UltralyticsDetectorProvider)*
(e.g. "face_yolov8m.pt")
– detects bbox containing the part to be ADetailed
- **SAMLoader (Impact)**
(e.g. "sam_vit_b_01ec64.pth")
– segment-anything-model to crop the target part out of the bbox
- **segm_detector** *(UltralyticsDetectorProvider)*
(e.g. "person_yolov8m-seg.pt")
– detects the cropped out shape and masks correspondingly
- **BBOX Threshold**
– probability of the detected part to match the query - faces : detected reliably → higher values work well ~ 0.7 - 0.8 - hands : more difficult to distinguish → lower values ~ 0.4 - 0.5
- **BBOX Dilation**
– expansion of the detected bboxes
- **Crop Factor**
– multiple of the bbox area to be considered as context
- **Drop Size**
– size in pixels below which a detection will be disregarded
→ helps prevent after-detailing negligible background detections
### ADetailer - **Guide Size**
– size maximum for detections to be considered
→ allows skipping areas that are large/detailed enough already
→ disregarded when force_inpaint = **enabled**
- **Inpaint Size**
– temporary size the masked area is upscaled to during generation
→ control over level of detail
→ disregarded when the masked area is larger already
- **Feather**
– softens the crop's edges for a smooth result
– also functions as noise_mask_feather
- **Cycle**
– allows multiple iterative passes
- **Noise Mask** ■ **enabled**    → context aware    → smooth, seamless result ■ **disabled**    → ignores context    → allows forcing out of context content    → requires further measures to blend in smoothly (_i.e. more inpainting_)    → denoise acts like opacity
- **Force Inpaint**
– bypasses threshold and size criteria when **enabled**

# Inpainting - **Grow Mask**
– expands the provided masks
- **Gaussian Blur**
– blurs the mask for smoother integration
- **Crop Factor**
– multiple of the bbox area to be considered as context
→ usual range: 1.5 - 3.0
- **Feather**
– softens the crop's edges for a smooth result
– also functions as noise_mask_feather
- **Inpaint Size**
– temporary size of **Mask** area multiplied by **crop_factor** during generation
→ control over level of detail
→ disregarded when the masked area is larger already
- **Noise Mask** ■ **enabled**    → context aware    → smooth, seamless result ■ **disabled**    → ignores context    → allows forcing out of context content    → requires further measures to blend in smoothly (_i.e. more inpainting_)    → denoise acts like opacity

## ► Nunchaku Installation (SVDQ) ### Automatic 1. Install the **ComfyUI-nunchaku** node pack and restart ComfyUI.
2. Open up and run the **Nunchaku_Installer** workflow, which contains a node that automatically installs the correct Nunchaku wheel for your system.
The *Installation Status* should something like

`✅ Successfully installed nunchaku-0.3.0+torch2.6-cp310-cp310-win_amd64.whl from GitHub Release.`

upon completion. > In case of download issues, try the other sources first.
If that doesn't help: - Check **ComfyUI-nunchaku**'s [**GitHub issues**](https://github.com/mit-han-lab/ComfyUI-nunchaku/issues) - Or **Manual Installation**   3. Done!
--- ### Manual 1. Download the correct [**Nunchaku wheel**](https://github.com/mit-han-lab/nunchaku/releases/tag/v0.3.0) corresponding to your Torch and Python version.
→ Both can be checked under ***System Info*** in the settings "*About*" section
2. Move the **.whl** file into `ComfyUI\python_embeded`
3. Open a command terminal in `ComfyUI\python_embeded` and install the wheel with this command modified to match your downloaded wheel's filename:

`python.exe -m pip install nunchaku-0.3.0+torch2.6-cp310-cp310-win_amd64.whl`

4. Done! --- ## Base SVDQuant models (*optional*) - [**Flux.1-Dev**](https://huggingface.co/mit-han-lab/svdq-int4-flux.1-dev/tree/main) | [**Flux.1-Schnell**](https://huggingface.co/mit-han-lab/svdq-int4-flux.1-schnell/tree/main)
→ download all files into a new folder named "**svdq-int4-flux.1-dev**" and place it in:
→ `ComfyUI\models\diffusion_models`
- [**T5xxl**](https://huggingface.co/mit-han-lab/nunchaku-t5/blob/main/awq-int4-flux.1-t5xxl.safetensors)
→ `ComfyUI\models\text_encoders`

# Pass Input Hijack > Allows the **Input Image** to act as a specific Pass' result to prevent regeneration. → To use simply load a completed/saved Pass or copy/paste the clipspace directly into the **Input Image** > Specifically SVDQuant models can not reproduce a generation even with exactly matching parameters (*non-deterministic*).
For example locking all seeds in and tweaking only the ADetailer pass would result in all passes being rerun, with different results.
→ The Hijack can circumvent that issue
